Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Meanwhile, trim the @butternut squash{1%unit}, halve lengthways, then scoop out the
seeds (peel first if you prefer). Cut into 2cm chunks.

Pop the diced butternut onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{}, sprinkle
over half the @curry powder mix{1/2%sachet} and season with @salt{} and
@black pepper{}. Toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

> Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}.
Turn halfway through.

== Basmati Rice ==

Meanwhile, pour the @water{300%ml}(for the rice) into a medium #saucepan{} with a
#tight-fitting lid{}. Stir in the @basmati rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and
bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with
the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still
covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to
serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

== Korma Style Curry ==

While everything cooks, halve any thick @Tenderstem® broccoli{80%g} stems
lengthways, then cut them into thirds.

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium heat. Once hot,
add the @korma curry paste{50%g}, garlic and remaining @curry powder mix{1/2%sachet}.
Stir-fry for ~{1%minute}, then stir in the @vegetable stock paste{10%g} and
@water{100%ml}(for the curry).

Drain the @king prawns{150%g}. Stir in the prawns and broccoli, then bring to
the boil. Once boiling, lower the heat, cover with a #lid{} and simmer until
the broccoli is just tender and the prawns are cooked through, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Next, stir in the @creme fraiche{150%g} and @mango chutney{40%g}. Bring back to
the boil, then remove from the heat. Season with @salt{} and @black pepper{}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns. They're
> cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Once the butternut squash is roasted, stir it through the curry. Return the pan
to the heat to warm through. Add a splash of water if it's a little too thick.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and share between your plates, then top with
your korma style curry. Enjoy!